{
  "The first step in a statistical capstone project is:": "",
  "Define a clear research question": "",
  "Collect data immediately": "",
  "Write the conclusion": "",
  "Run a hypothesis test": "",
  "A focused research question directs every subsequent step, from data collection to analysis to interpretation.": "",
  "Good data sources for a capstone project include:": "",
  "Unverified social media posts that may contain biased or fabricated information": "",
  "Government databases, academic datasets, and properly conducted surveys": "",
  "Wikipedia edits that have not been peer-reviewed or verified by domain experts": "",
  "Personal opinions from friends and family without any systematic data collection": "",
  "Reputable, systematically collected data sources produce reliable and credible analyses.": "",
  "Exploratory data analysis (EDA) involves:": "",
  "Skipping directly to conclusions": "",
  "Only running hypothesis tests": "",
  "Only collecting more data": "",
  "Computing summary statistics and creating visualizations to understand the data": "",
  "EDA helps you understand patterns, outliers, and distributions before conducting formal analysis.": "",
  "Before performing a hypothesis test in a capstone, you must:": "",
  "Always use a z-test regardless": "",
  "Assume normality without checking": "",
  "Check that the conditions for the test are met": "",
  "Skip checking assumptions": "",
  "Condition-checking validates that the chosen procedure's conclusions are reliable for the given data.": "",
  "Choosing the right statistical test depends on:": "",
  "Only the hypothesis being tested, without considering data type or sample characteristics": "",
  "The type of data (categorical vs. quantitative), number of groups, and research question": "",
  "Only sample size, which determines the test regardless of the type of data collected": "",
  "Random choice among available tests, since all statistical methods produce equivalent results": "",
  "Test selection follows logically from the type of data you have and the question you are trying to answer.": "",
  "A well-structured statistical report includes:": "",
  "Introduction, methods, results, and discussion sections": "",
  "Only p-values listed in a table without any supporting context or explanation": "",
  "Only the conclusion section, skipping the methods and results entirely for brevity": "",
  "Only graphs displayed without axes labels, titles, or accompanying written interpretation": "",
  "A complete report covers every stage of the analysis, from question formulation through interpretation.": "",
  "If your hypothesis test fails to reject H₀ in a capstone project:": "",
  "H₀ has been proven true": "",
  "The project has failed": "",
  "There was insufficient evidence to support Hₐ, which is still a valid and informative result": "",
  "You should change your data until you get significance": "",
  "Failing to reject H₀ is a legitimate statistical outcome that contributes to scientific knowledge.": "",
  "Discussing limitations in a capstone is important because:": "",
  "It reduces your grade because it highlights weaknesses in the research design used": "",
  "It weakens your project by drawing attention to problems that reviewers might overlook": "",
  "It shows critical thinking about potential biases and generalizability": "",
  "It is unnecessary because a well-designed project has no limitations worth discussing": "",
  "Honest discussion of limitations strengthens a project's credibility and shows mature scientific thinking.": "",
  "Ethical data collection in a capstone project requires:": "",
  "Using only online sources": "",
  "Manipulating data to achieve significance": "",
  "Obtaining informed consent, protecting privacy, and reporting results honestly": "",
  "Collecting data from anyone without consent": "",
  "Research ethics, including consent and honest reporting, are mandatory even for class projects.": "",
  "Reproducibility in a capstone project means:": "",
  "Documenting your methods clearly enough that someone else could repeat the analysis": "",
  "Hiding your methods": "",
  "Never sharing your code": "",
  "Using proprietary data no one else can access": "",
  "Transparency in methods is a core scientific principle that allows others to verify and build on your work.": "",
  "What is a confounding variable?": "",
  "A variable that affects both the explanatory and response variables, distorting the observed relationship": "",
  "A variable that never appears in observational studies": "",
  "The same thing as the response variable": "",
  "A variable that improves the analysis by adding precision": "",
  "Confounders create spurious associations or mask true effects because they are related to both the explanatory and response variables.": "",
  "What is the purpose of proper sampling in a capstone project?": "",
  "To ensure the sample is as small as possible": "",
  "To include only people you know": "",
  "To ensure results can generalize to the population of interest": "",
  "To introduce bias deliberately": "",
  "Representative sampling is the foundation of valid statistical inference, allowing conclusions to extend beyond the sample.": "",
  "What does the discussion section of a statistical report accomplish?": "",
  "It only restates the numerical results from the analysis without adding interpretation": "",
  "It avoids any interpretation and simply presents raw output from the statistical software": "",
  "It interprets results in context, compares findings to expectations, and notes limitations": "",
  "It only lists p-values and test statistics without discussing their practical implications": "",
  "The discussion section connects statistical findings to real-world meaning and acknowledges the scope of the conclusions.": "",
  "What is the role of a confidence interval in a capstone project?": "",
  "It eliminates all uncertainty about the parameter": "",
  "It proves causation": "",
  "It gives the exact value of the population parameter": "",
  "It provides a range of plausible values for the population parameter with a stated confidence level": "",
  "CIs quantify the precision of the estimate, showing a plausible range for the true parameter value.": "",
  "What does 'describing the shape of data' mean in EDA?": "",
  "Only computing the mean and reporting it as the sole summary of the data distribution": "",
  "Using histograms, boxplots, and descriptive language (symmetric, skewed, bimodal, etc.) to characterize the distribution": "",
  "Drawing only scatterplots to display the relationship between two quantitative variables": "",
  "Only running t-tests to determine whether the data differs significantly from a benchmark": "",
  "Shape description combines visual displays with verbal characterization to understand the distribution before formal inference.": "",
  "What makes a scatter plot useful in a capstone project?": "",
  "It replaces the need for any other analysis": "",
  "It shows the relationship between two quantitative variables, revealing direction, form, and strength": "",
  "It shows categorical proportions": "",
  "It displays only one variable": "",
  "Scatterplots display bivariate quantitative relationships, helping identify patterns that might be modeled with regression.": "",
  "What does including a regression equation in a capstone report allow?": "",
  "Use only for categorical data where the response variable has distinct non-numeric levels": "",
  "Nothing useful, because regression equations provide no meaningful statistical information": "",
  "Replacement of all other statistical analysis, making additional tests and summaries unnecessary": "",
  "Prediction of the response variable and quantification of the relationship between variables": "",
  "A regression equation allows both prediction and quantification of the association between variables.": "",
  "What is the purpose of reflection at the end of a capstone project?": "",
  "It is only required for the teacher": "",
  "It is a waste of time": "",
  "It helps solidify understanding and identifies areas for growth": "",
  "It does not contribute to learning": "",
  "Reflection deepens learning by encouraging you to consider what worked, what was challenging, and how you would improve.": "",
  "What makes visualizations effective in a capstone report?": "",
  "Making them as complex as possible": "",
  "Clearly communicating key patterns with appropriate labels, titles, and support for the conclusions": "",
  "They are optional in a report": "",
  "Using as many colors and effects as possible": "",
  "Effective graphs highlight important patterns without unnecessary clutter and directly support the written analysis.": "",
  "What does a strong capstone project demonstrate?": "",
  "Speed of completion, finishing the project as quickly as possible without thorough analysis": "",
  "Only one statistical technique applied to the data without exploring alternative approaches": "",
  "Only memorization of formulas without any attempt at interpretation or contextual discussion": "",
  "Integration of descriptive statistics, inference, graphical analysis, and contextual interpretation": "",
  "Capstone projects showcase comprehensive statistical thinking by combining multiple skills and methods.": "",
  "A student is designing a capstone project to investigate whether study time is associated with GPA among college freshmen. She plans to survey 200 freshmen at her university. Which research question is most appropriate?": "",
  "Does studying cause higher GPAs among all college students regardless of other variables involved": "",
  "What is the average GPA of freshmen enrolled at this particular university this academic year": "",
  "Do students who study more always get 4.0 GPAs as a direct and guaranteed result of their effort": "",
  "'Is there a significant linear association between weekly study hours and GPA among freshmen at this university?'": "",
  "A good research question is specific, testable, and appropriately scoped. Since this is an observational study (survey), it should ask about association, not causation.": "",
  "During EDA for her capstone, a student creates a histogram of household income data and finds it is strongly right-skewed. She needs to report the center and spread. Which measures should she use?": "",
  "Mode and range, because they are simplest": "",
  "Mean and range, because they use all the data": "",
  "Mean and standard deviation, because they are always the best measures": "",
  "Median and IQR, because they are resistant to the skewness and outliers in the data": "",
  "For skewed distributions, the median and IQR are preferred because they are resistant to the influence of extreme values in the tail.": "",
  "A capstone project examines whether there is a difference in average test scores between students who used a new online platform and those who did not. The student has n₁ = 45 (platform users, mean = 82, s = 10) and n₂ = 50 (non-users, mean = 77, s = 12). Which test should she use and what are the hypotheses?": "",
  "One-proportion z-test; H₀: p = 0.5": "",
  "Chi-square test; H₀: scores are independent of platform use": "",
  "Two-sample t-test; H₀: μ₁ = μ₂, Hₐ: μ₁ ≠ μ₂": "",
  "Paired t-test; H₀: μ_d = 0": "",
  "Two independent groups with quantitative data require a two-sample t-test. The hypotheses compare the population means of the two groups.": "",
  "A student's capstone regression of daily temperature (x, in degrees F) vs. ice cream sales (y, in dollars) yields ŷ = −200 + 8.5x with r² = 0.71. The residual plot shows random scatter. The student is asked to interpret r² in the discussion section. Which interpretation is correct?": "",
  "The correlation is 0.71": "",
  "71% of the variation in daily ice cream sales is explained by the linear relationship with temperature": "",
  "Temperature predicts 71% of all days correctly": "",
  "71% of ice cream sales are caused by temperature": "",
  "r² = 0.71 means 71% of the variability in ice cream sales is accounted for by the linear relationship with temperature. It does not imply causation.": "",
  "In her capstone, a student surveys 120 people about their preferred exercise type (running, swimming, cycling) and age group (under 30, 30-50, over 50). She wants to know if exercise preference is associated with age group. Which test is appropriate, and what is the key condition?": "",
  "Linear regression; check residual plot": "",
  "ANOVA; equal variances required": "",
  "Two-sample t-test; condition is normality": "",
  "Chi-square test of independence; all expected counts must be at least 5": "",
  "Two categorical variables in a two-way table call for a chi-square test of independence. The key condition is that all expected cell counts are at least 5.": "",
  "A student collects data on sleep hours and GPA for 80 students. After finding a significant positive correlation (r = 0.45, p = 0.002), she writes: 'Getting more sleep causes higher GPAs.' What is wrong with this conclusion?": "",
  "Nothing; the p-value proves causation between sleep hours and GPA in this student population": "",
  "She should have used a chi-square test instead because both variables are measured numerically": "",
  "The correlation is too weak to draw any conclusion about the relationship between the variables": "",
  "This is an observational study, so she can only claim an association, not causation. Confounding variables (e.g., time management skills) may explain the relationship.": "",
  "Observational studies cannot establish causation because confounding variables may be responsible for the observed association.": "",
  "A capstone project investigates whether a new tutoring program improves math scores. The student uses a matched pairs design: 25 students take a pre-test, attend tutoring, then take a post-test. The mean difference (post − pre) is 6.2 points with s_d = 8.5. She computes t = 6.2/(8.5/√25) = 3.65 with df = 24 and p < 0.001. What should she conclude?": "",
  "The tutoring program had no effect because 6.2 points is not a meaningful improvement in math": "",
  "The improvement of 6.2 is too small to be meaningful regardless of what the p-value indicates": "",
  "The result is not significant because n is less than 30, which violates the normal condition": "",
  "There is convincing evidence that the tutoring program is associated with an increase in math scores, with a mean improvement of about 6.2 points": "",
  "With t = 3.65 and p < 0.001, there is strong evidence of a significant improvement. The conclusion should be in context and note that without a control group, other factors could contribute.": "",
  "A student's capstone data contains a potential outlier: one participant reported studying 80 hours per week while all others reported between 5 and 35 hours. What should the student do in the limitations section?": "",
  "Delete the outlier and say nothing about it in the report to avoid complicating the analysis": "",
  "Acknowledge the outlier, investigate whether it is a data entry error or genuine, and report results both with and without it to assess its influence": "",
  "Ignore it because outliers always exist in real datasets and do not warrant special attention": "",
  "Change the value to 35 to match the rest of the data so the analysis is not affected by it": "",
  "Transparent handling of outliers includes investigating the cause, reporting results with and without the value, and discussing the impact in the limitations section.": "",
  "A student's capstone computes a 95% confidence interval of (2.1, 8.3) for the mean difference in test scores between two teaching methods. Her friend says this means there is a 95% probability the true difference is in this interval. How should the student correct this interpretation?": "",
  "The student should explain that we are 95% confident the interval captures the true difference; the true difference is a fixed value, not random, so probability language is incorrect": "",
  "Her friend is correct; no correction is needed because 95% confidence means the true value is probably there": "",
  "The interval should be recomputed at 99% to be correct because 95% confidence is insufficient for this claim": "",
  "95% of students would get the same interval if they repeated the study with the same sample size and design": "",
  "The true parameter is fixed. The 95% refers to the long-run success rate of the procedure: if we repeated the study many times, about 95% of the resulting intervals would capture the true difference.": "",
  "A student completes a capstone analyzing factors affecting home prices. She used multiple regression, checked conditions, reported r² = 0.68, found significant predictors, and discussed limitations. For the reflection, she notes her biggest takeaway. Which reflection best demonstrates comprehensive statistical thinking?": "",
  "I memorized the regression formula and was able to apply it correctly to the dataset without difficulty": "",
  "'I learned that real data is messy: checking conditions revealed violations I had to address, confounders limited my causal claims, and my model only explained 68% of the variation, reminding me that statistical models simplify complex reality.'": "",
  "I got a significant p-value, so the project was successful and all of my hypotheses were confirmed by the data": "",
  "I learned how to use a calculator for regression and can now compute slopes and intercepts quickly and accurately": "",
  "A strong reflection addresses the challenges of real data analysis, the importance of conditions and limitations, and the recognition that models are imperfect representations of reality.": ""
}